      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Version-controlled codebase with documented training pipeline and dependency manifest.",
      "rationale": "The ML surrogate training pipeline is maintained under Git version control. A requirements manifest (Python 3.10, TensorFlow 2.12, scikit-learn 1.3) is archived alongside the model checkpoint. Unit tests cover data-loading and preprocessing routines. SQA level 1 requirements are met at MRL 2."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver used to generate training labels verified against analytical benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "The ANSYS Fluent CFD solver used to generate the 6 000-point training dataset has been verified against the FDA benchmark nozzle case and internal laminar-pipe-flow analytical solutions. Verification residuals are below 1 % for all quantities of interest. The ML code itself does not perform numerical integration and is not subject to classical numerical verification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid-convergence index (GCI) < 5 % for hemolysis index across all training operating points.",
      "rationale": "A mesh-independence study was conducted on three successively refined grids (2.1 M, 4.8 M, 9.6 M cells) at two bounding operating points. GCI values for the scalar hemolysis index were 3.1 % and 2.7 % respectively, both below the 5 % threshold. The 4.8 M-cell mesh was used for all 6 000 training simulations."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation test conditions span the intended COU operating envelope (1.5–5.0 L/min, 2 000–4 500 rpm).",
      "rationale": "The 1 200-point test set covers the full five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU: {1.5, 2.5, 3.5, 4.5, 5.0} L/min × {2 000, 2 500, 3 000, 3 500, 4 500} rpm. All test conditions correspond to nominal steady-state pump operation. Conditions are drawn from the same Latin-hypercube design used to construct the training set, ensuring coverage of the COU envelope under nominal assumptions."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted RH within ±10 % of CFD reference across all test points; R² ≥ 0.95.",
      "rationale": "On the 1 200-point nominal test set, the ML surrogate achieved R² = 0.97 and maximum absolute deviation of 8.4 % relative to CFD reference values. All predictions satisfied the ±10 % acceptance band. Comparison was limited to the nominal operating distribution; no out-of-distribution or perturbed-condition comparisons were performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoI (relative hemolysis index RH) directly maps to the clinical acceptance criterion RH < 1.",
      "rationale": "The surrogate model outputs the scalar relative hemolysis index RH derived from the Giersiepen–Wurzinger power-law model integrated along Lagrangian particle paths. RH is the quantity used in predicate-device comparison under FDA guidance. The mapping from model output to decision criterion is direct and unambiguous."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation activities address the same device geometry, fluid, and operating envelope as the COU.",
      "rationale": "All validation simulations used the FDA generic centrifugal blood pump geometry, bovine blood rheology (Newtonian approximation, μ = 0.0035 Pa·s), and the five flow-speed combinations specified in the COU. Validation activities are therefore directly relevant to the COU. The scope of validation does not extend beyond the nominal operating envelope defined at model development time."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence to residual < 1e-5 for all CFD training runs.",
      "rationale": "All 6 000 CFD simulations used to generate training labels were run to scaled residuals below 1×10⁻⁵ for continuity, momentum, and turbulence quantities. Convergence was confirmed via monitor-point stabilisation of the hemolysis index. No diverged or unconverged runs were included in the training dataset."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented inference procedure with input-range guards preventing out-of-envelope queries.",
      "rationale": "A deployment wrapper enforces input-range guards that reject inference requests outside the training envelope (flow rate 1.5–5.0 L/min, rotational speed 2 000–4 500 rpm). An operator manual documents the required input format and units. These controls reduce the risk of use error to a level consistent with MRL 2 requirements."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Model-form uncertainty assessment is not required at Model Risk Level 2 for this factor. The ML surrogate architecture (fully connected neural network, 4 hidden layers, 128 neurons per layer, ReLU activations) was selected based on cross-validation performance on the nominal training distribution. No formal model-form uncertainty quantification was conducted."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Sensitivity of model outputs to input uncertainty is not required at MRL 2. Input parameters (flow rate, rotational speed, five geometric tolerance dimensions) were treated as deterministic at their nominal values throughout training and validation. No parametric uncertainty propagation was performed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 1,
      "achievedLevel": 1,
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Not required at MRL 2 for this factor.",
      "rationale": "Formal characterisation of test-sample representativeness beyond coverage of the nominal operating envelope is not required at MRL 2. The 1 200-point test set was drawn by stratified random sampling from the same Latin-hypercube design as the training set."
    },
    {
